 Dead roosters in Oita Prefecture raise bird flu fears
 -----------------------------------------------------
 .
 [1] Thailand
 [2]-[4] Japan
 New outbreak in Thailand; Bird flu scare; Virus re-emerges in 9 provinces
 Newin faults fighting cocks; vet disagrees
 ----------------------------------------------
 Bird flu disease has re-emerged in poultry in 9 provinces, with officials 
 blaming unregulated movement of fighting roosters for the 2nd wave of the 
 epidemic.
 Deputy Agriculture Minister Newin Chidchob said random checks at 14 spots 
 confirmed the H5N1 strain of the flu had struck again. The check was 
 performed in 9 provinces, 8 of which had originally been declared bird flu-
 affected "red zones", marked for strict quarantine, and then been downgraded 
 to "yellow zones", marked for surveillance.
 8 provinces are experiencing a recurrence of the outbreak: Chaiyaphum, 
 Uthai Thani, Uttaradit, Sukhothai, Kanchanaburi, Nakhon Pathom, Petchaburi, 
 and Phangnga.  The 9th province, Roi Et, is having its 1st outbreak of the 
 virus.
 Newin said 10 300 samples from poultry, possible flu carriers, had been 
 collected since 12 Feb 2004 from the red zones and 427 samples from the 
 yellow zones, where movements of poultry were banned without a transport 
 certificate. He said the flu was found in 20 percent of all the samples in 
 the red zones.  In the flu-emerging provinces, the infection was present 
 mostly in fighting roosters.
 In Roi Et, the flu came from "nomadic ducks" transported to open fields to 
 graze for food such as snail pests.
 In the 8 provinces, all poultry within a 1km radius of the outbreak epicentre 
 was being destroyed.
 Newin said infected fighting roosters smuggled out of red zones during 
 the first outbreak and then brought back to the areas had probably 
 re-ignited the infection.
 In Roi Et, poultry would be culled in a 5km radius as this was the 1st time 
 the flu had been reported in the province. A poultry movement ban was also 
 imposed.
 Some owners have refused to slaughter their prized fighting roosters.
 Newin expected the latest culling operation to take no more than 72 hours.
 Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra downplayed fears of the re-emerging flu, 
 saying the government would carry out 3 spot checks every 21 days after the 
 initial outbreak to ensure the virus was eradicated.  He said the 1st 
 quarantine period may not root out the infection but subsequent rounds 
 would do the trick.
 Deputy Prime Minister Somkid Jatusripitak, who oversees the flu situation, 
 said the fact the disease had returned in the same red zones showed the 
 viral spread had been contained.
 Jiroj Sasipreeyajan, of Chulalongkorn University's faculty of veterinary 
 science, said the detection of the bird flu virus in yellow surveillance 
 zones was due to the failure to eradicate all fowl in the epidemic area.  
 Birds in their natural habitats should also be culled, not just chickens, Dr 
 Jiroj said.  The Ministry of Agriculture needed to work more closely with the 
 Ministry of Natural Resources and the Environment, he said. 
 He did not believe the reappearance of the H5N1 strain in Thailand would 
 damage the nation's credibility in dealing with the bird flu epidemic. 
 Concealing a report on bird flu discovery was more shameful than it being 
 detected again, Dr Jiroj said. A 2nd round of detection was not unusual for 
 such a highly infectious virus. He disagreed with the Ministry of 
 Agriculture's assertion that owners of fighting cocks were to blame.
 [If birds smuggled from an infected zone to a non-infected zone are the 
 reason the non-infected zone becomes infected, the smuggler is responsible 
 for the infection. It does not matter whether their occupation is raising 
 layers or fighting cocks, it is the smuggler who is responsible. The 
 motivations in this case are likely related to fighting -- either actually 
 fighting the birds or acquiring their genetics.
 Newcastle disease in California in 2003 was associated with fighting cocks; 
 now the issue is Avian Influenza in fighting cocks. How may cases of Avian 
 Influenza in humans have been associated with cock fighting?
 Certainly, these regions in Thailand will have to be very diligent in the 
 surveillance of this disease. � Mod.TG]
 The National Institute of Animal Health has confirmed that the dead 
 poultry, a cluster of suspected victims of the second outbreak of Highly 
 Pathogenic Avian Influenza in Oita Prefecture, had been "infected with 
 influenza virus (A/H5)."
 - All birds raised in the affected facility has been dead or destroyed.
 - The facility has been disinfected.
 - Officials are to take necessary measures to prevent the outbreak 
 from spreading.
