 A case of bird flu is suspected in the town of Kokonoe in Oita Prefecture 
 following the deaths of bantam roosters kept as pets, the Ministry of 
 Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries said Tuesday.
 2 of 7 dead roosters tested positive for bird flu, and the National 
 Institute of Animal Health is conducting confirmation tests, ministry 
 officials said.  The ministry will find out the results in the evening, 
 they said.
 They said a household in the southwestern Japan town kept the 7 bantam 
 roosters along with 6 other roosters and 1 duck.
 The 6 other roosters and duck have been killed for testing to determine 
 whether all 14 had been infected. If infections are confirmed, this will 
 mark the 2nd outbreak of bird flu in Japan following the country's first in 
 79 years at a poultry farm in Yamaguchi Prefecture, detected 12 Jan 2004. 
 About 34 000 chickens were depopulated in the Yamaguchi case.
 According to ministry officials, a local animal health sanitary facility 
 reported the suspected case to the ministry Monday night via the Oita 
 prefectural government.  The household found 3 dead roosters Saturday and 4 
 others Sunday. It reported the findings to the Oita prefectural government 
 Sunday, they said.  The ministry has banned public access to the area and 
 sterilized chicken coops.
 About 570 000 chickens, or 1/3 of the total chickens raised in Oita 
 Prefecture, are kept within a 30-kilometer radius of the household in 
 question, a local livestock official said.
 The bird flu outbreak in Yamaguchi Prefecture has been traced to the same 
 strain as the H5N1 bird flu virus found in South Korea and Vietnam, which 
 have seen large-scale bird flu epidemics since late in 2003.
 Similar epidemics have also emerged in Thailand, Indonesia, and China. Some 
 people infected with the bird flu virus have died.
 Masato Tashiro, a senior researcher at the National Institute of Infectious 
 Diseases, said the suspected case in Oita Prefecture may have no link to 
 the Yamaguchi farm and could be contained easily.
